A problem is a puzzle, to which there are multiple solutions. My innate hunger for knowledge and puzzle solving mentality drives me to find new sources of information and solutions through working in teams, thinking laterally and exploring non-standard avenues that may at first glance seem unrelated. Succinctly put, creativity. Regerdless of my position and tasks within a team, I work to the very best of my ability to achieve qualitative results; leading a group and distributing activities not dissimilar to a SCRUM master under AGILE project management.

AboutAbout

Hi, I am Leonardo and I am a recently graduated student with a BSc degree in Mechanical Engineering at the University of Twente. Throughout my experience at this University, I have obtained useful knowledge in several areas such as mechanics, SolidWorks, calculus, production management, etc. One of the the areas where my interest is the highest is materials science, more specifically, polymers. It is precisely for this reason that I chose my Bachelor Thesis Assignment to be carried out at the Elastomer Technology & Engineering Department at the University of Twente, where I analyzed the Rheological and Mechanical properties of rubber compounds.
I also have a huge interest in other areas like the energy sector, semiconductors, manufacturing and production processes, and interdisciplinary projects.

From a general perspective, I can define myself as a responsible, hard-working, and creative person who is aware that the only way to improve is to force myself to continuous challenges. This way I am looking for a job in which I am able to test what I have learned during the last three years, and most importantly, I can broaden and enhance my knowledge and skill set.Hi, I am Leonardo and I am a recently graduated student with a BSc degree in Mechanical Engineering at the University of Twente. I am from Georgia (the country) and currently live in the Netherlands. I have a Dutch partner and we try to split our time in between these two beautiful countries. I am a miniatures enthusiast, I enjoy making as well as collecting miniature versions of real life items. Enjoying Georgian cuisine with my friends and family is what I cherish the most.

I have obtained master's degree in Mathematics at Utrecht University. I conducted a research in the intersection of mathematics and AI, more specifically: ‘Incorporating Deep Learning Models for Forecasting Dutch Inflation’ (grade 9).

AboutAbout

I completed my Master's in Sustainability Science and Policy at Maastricht University in the Netherlands. I have completed my Bachelor's in Environmental Science and Mathematics from Hollins University in the United States.

My research interests lie in waste management and natural resources conservation. I am also interested in working with local communities to initiate local resources conservation programs. During my Bachelor, I studied a semester abroad in Cambodia and Vietnam where I interviewed members of community forest and community fishery. It was inspiring to discover that local communities were coming together to protect the remaining forest and re-build the ones that were destroyed during the war.

Before joining Maastricht University, I have had the opportunity to intern at American Rivers, Climate Central, and the University of Kansas. These internships helped me to foster my research skills, time management, and provided opportunities to work in group settings. I also worked as a Resident Assistant at Hollins University for three years where I gained experience in community building, and conflict management, and mediation.

Apart from academia, I enjoy gardening, traveling, hiking, knitting, cooking, and watching movies. I also enjoy learning about the histories and cultures of places that I have visited and I want to visit.I completed my Master's in Sustainability Science and Policy at Maastricht University in the Netherlands.   • Fruit flies in California: Are they established or do detections represent new introductions? (Research Advisors: Dr. Jean Fallon, Dr. Daniel Derringer and Dr. Jonathan Walter)Fruit flies in California: Are they established or do detections represent new introductions? (Research Advisors: Dr. Jean Fallon, Dr. Daniel Derringer and Dr. Jonathan Walter)
    Feb 2017 - May 2017Feb 2017 - May 2017
      Associated with Hollins UniversityAssociated with Hollins University
      • Here we used detection data of four species of fruit flies (medfly, Mexican fruit fly, guava fruit fly, and oriental fruit fly) in California and analyzed those data to examine whether these fruit flies’ species were established in California, or the detections represented new introductions. Factors influencing where and when insect pest invasions occur include; climate; human activities such as trade, migration, and transportation; and natural dispersal by the organism. To evaluate effects of these factors, we applied a set generalized additive models (GAMS) analogous to logistic regression to detection data for each species. We examined three different models: space-only, time-only and time and space to study detection nature of fruit flies. We evaluated the space-only and time-only model to isolate spatial and temporal patterns. AboutAbout

I have always had a love for numbers. I started my professional journey by pursuing a bachelor's degree in Financial Mathematics with a minor in Accounting at USC. I knew I wanted to do something technical, but I wasn't entirely sure what direction I wanted to explore.

After graduation, I worked as a management consultant at Xelay Acumen in the San Francisco Area. Working as a consultant taught me how to be highly efficient by planning, communicating, and organizing my work effectively. I learned about the value of the 80/20 mindset and how it can accelerate my output.

Living in the SF Bay Area, I saw firsthand how software disrupted almost every industry, and I knew I wanted to be a part of it. I decided to go back to school to specialize in computer science, and I am confident I made the right decision. Being a software engineer complements my background very well. It also allows me to use entrepreneurial spirit to create a lasting product or business with little to no financial investment. All I need to do is sit down behind my laptop and start coding.

While pursuing my degree in computer science at USC, I have gained two years of work experience as a software engineer, and this has taught me many valuable lessons.

Working as a software engineer at the Jin Shin Institute since 2019 taught me how to drive a project with limited technical support. I created a fully functional mobile app in Swift entirely from scratch and designed each part of the application for performance and scalability.

Interning as a full-stack developer on the App Engine team at Blend gave me the opportunity to take ownership of the full development cycle and pick up new skills along the way. I never realized how much passion I had for learning until I pushed myself to absorb as much as I could every day. Learning how to navigate large codebases and rapidly implement changes was the most valuable thing I learned over the summer.

Doing the Walt Disney capstone project taught me that culture is the most important factor of success. Early on in the project, I began to see that not everyone valued the project equally and that the team culture needed to change for the team to perform better. During the next team meeting, I asked if we could hold each other more accountable. Over the next few weeks, individual members started to put more effort into their parts and become key contributors to the project. Motivating others to make significant contributions to the product makes me proud. I am very dedicated to what I do, and I will always aim to get the best out of people.I have always had a love for numbers. AboutAbout

I am a firm believer that if you want something, you need to go for it. This also means you have to give your full 100% to achieve what you want.

When I just finished my Master's I decided I wanted to start working for a multinational company and be able to move to a far away country after a few year to experience the life of a working person abroad. For this I chose Avanade. At first it looked like my ambition to go far away wasn't going to work out, so I decided to go to China on my own to study Chinese (this is a hobby of mine :)). After this small break I again applied myself to be allowed to be transfer abroad, and this time it worked out! I truly enjoyed my time in Los Angeles and learning about all the differences between the US and the Netherlands both small and big.

After a bit over a year, however, I decided I wanted to be closer to my family and friends in the Netherlands (a 9 hour time difference makes staying in touch difficult) and so I moved back to the Netherlands. With this transition back, I also decided it was time for me to broaden my experience in IT away from ERP systems and consultancy. I also wanted to find a job that I can honestly say I love instead of I like. In this search I work for both Nationale Nederlanden and Hogeschool Rotterdam for a short time, until I found that job that I can say I love at Hogeschool Utrecht.

At Hogeschool Utrecht I am a teacher and coach for the Open ICT bachelor program. In this work I get to guide students into becoming IT professionals. The program is structured in such a way that students work in teams on real projects. We work with SCRUM and every two weeks the students have to show their progress to either their internal Product Owner (i.e., a teacher), or their external Product Owner from the company that facilitates their project. Next to this, I get talk with every student I coach at least once every two weeks in a one-on-one session to discuss their progress and check how they are doing. Next to coaching, I also am part of two Guilds, Backend and Computer Engineering. These Guilds are the knowledge centers for the roles that students can choose in our program, where we share knowledge and review work.

My interest in the Computer Science domain are relatively broad, but a short list of topics that interest me is:
- Cloud
- Home Automation
- Game Development
- Game AI

AboutAbout

My interests lie in the area of developing people, organisations, and organisational forms. I have experience as a facilitator and coach, as well as being a mindfulness practitioner. Aside from that, I cultivate a hobbyist fascination in evolution theory and complex systems theory.

I maintain that I am a theorist at heart and a pragmatist by choice. If it were up to me, I would love to have all knowledge derived from first principles; abstractly, theoretically, beautifully. But until we meet our maker, we shall be humbled time and time again. Therefore, wisdom would allow a certain amount of testing and tinkering, trial and error. So do we overcome our prejudice and dialogue with nature, who alone knows herself in her full entirety.

I have had the good fortune of living in several different countries and collaborating with people across disciplines, cultures and continents. This has helped me develop empathy, communication skills and intellectual openness. Along the way, I've become fluent in five languages which continues to be an immense source of joy.

As part of my Master in Management programme at Rotterdam School of Management, I did my thesis at Aberkyn, a subsidiary of McKinsey & Company. My research looked into ways to proactively harness chance elements by generating, identifying and making use of fruitful unexpected events.

Together with a couple of brave people at Breathe, I am now "Building Inspired Companies" and working to nudge mainstream business to be of greater service to the whole. AboutAbout

I am an Assistant Professor at the Department of Applied Physics at Eindhoven University of Technology. My research activity is at the interface between complex flowing matter, physics for society and machine learning for nonlinear physical systems. Since 2012, in the context of the "Crowdflow" topical group, my goal is to advance our fundamental understanding of pedestrian crowd flows. I aim at quantitative models for the emergent physics of crowds to allow safer and more efficient pedestrian environments. To this purpose, in collaboration with national and international facility managers of, e.g., municipalities, museums, and festivals, I established numerous real-life crowd tracking experiments. I am furthermore active in the application of recent machine and deep learning techniques to the analysis of highly complex and non-linear physical systems and, in particular, fluid turbulence.

I have extensive experience in high-reliability/high-performance sofware. I hold a Ph.D. in Applied Mathematics from the Centre for Analysis, Scientific computing and Applications, Dept. of Mathematics, Eindhoven University of Techonology, NL, and a second Ph.D. in Structural Engineering from the Department of Structural, Geotechnical and Building Engineering, Polytechnic University of Turin, IT.I am an Assistant Professor at the Department of Applied Physics at Eindhoven University of Technology.     • Show project
      • Los Alamos Plasma Simulation (LAPS) is an integrated modeling code based on a common-data framework for multiphysics simulation of both magnetic and inertial confinment fusion (ICF) plasmas. Its principal design goal is to provide a common data structure on computational grids and plasma states for different components of the multiphysics integration. LAPS provides an optimal mesh generation for one to three dimensional configuration space discretization and an adaptive mesh scheme that equi-distributes application-specified error. The plasma state is defined on this mesh. LAPS supports the solution of moment and kinetic equations using grids, particle-in-cell, Monte-Carlo, and molecular dynamics. The parallel data structure and (non)linear solvers for PDEs are based on PETSc, while the parallel data structure and communication for particle and Monte-Carlo method are native to LAPS. LAPS separates the numerical discretization from application PDEs. The initial focus is on spectral method, including the spectral element/volume and discontinuous Garlekin scheme for conservative PDEs. The initial set of applications for LAPS development include PIC modeling of plasma transport and rotation in field reversed configuration, fluid-moment and kinetic model of tokamak scrape-off layer; a two-fluids plasma model of spherical implosion for ICF.

        • We develop two different binary classification models for classifying two types of users, users with and without a job. We use the discrete time Markov model and the long short-term memory neural network for this. The choice for this specific binary classifier is - sort of - arbitrary, yet serves as a building block for more sophisticated and more extensive classifiers. For training the classifiers, we use a user's daily semantic location sequences over a certain period with known job status as input. It is shown that a DTMC performs well in classifying these types of users by comparing its performance in the form of the balanced accuracy with the performance of the baseline LSTM neural network. Classification is done by calculating the Jensen-Shannon distance between users, which can be interpreted as a distance between their Markov models.

        • The large amount of mobility behavior data of people collected by companies can provide insights into how people move over the day. The software of Mobidot captures via GPS 24/7 the mobility behavior of Dutch individuals and groups over the whole world via their mobile phones. Mobidot has a rule-based method to determine the purposes of trips during the activity recognition phase. Examples of activities are working, shopping, and leisure. The company's ultimate overall goal is to find a method to build a complete user profile which serves as an input to an improved activity recognition via the rule-based method. The improved activity recognition would provide valuable answers to Mobidot's customers for market research, panel surveys, urban policy development, and impact evaluation. As an example, the data can be used as an input for government policies to achieve a smoother and better distributed traffic flow.

          However, there are trips with hard to recognize purposes (still `unknown’). Strategies are developed to reduce this category. This is done by first performing 5-fold cross validation to filter a high-quality training set and a obtain good discriminating feature set. Finally, this set is applied to the test set with `unknown' journeys.     • Grade: 8.0Grade: 8.0
      • The concept of tie strength can be used to analyze interactions. It describes the strength of your friendship with one of your friends. It increases when an interaction takes place, and then decays continuously over time if no new interaction takes place. This concept can be very useful to find the most important connections in a social network.

        This paper investigates the influence of popularity on the tie strength in such tie-decay networks. To model popularity, we use an interaction probability between 2 persons at every time step, which depends on their popularities, the number of people in the network and the average popularity among all people in the network. The results of this analysis are used to analyze real life data of interactions. By analyzing this data, the distributions of real-world tie strength are determined. Hi there, my name is Maik Overmars and I am currently PhD student at the Mathematics of Operations Research group at the University of Twente. The fields I specialize are Data Science and Stochastic Operations Research. Topics from these fields that interest me are machine learning and solving decision making problems among others.

As an Applied Mathematician my passion is to use mathematics to solve real world problems. I think I'm at my best when I apply mathematical methods to model these problems. Due to its generality, such methods can be applied in very many cases.

I'm a calm worker who is great at working on problems individually. However, I enjoy it most when I work on a project in a team.     European Journal of Personality · Feb 28, 2022European Journal of Personality · Feb 28, 2022
    • Show publication
      • Family and friends are central to human life and well-being. Most people maintain both family and friendship relationships and these relationships might show interdependencies that have scarcely been addressed. We examined the relative frequency of daily contact with family and friends (i.e. friends/family-contact) and its link with personality traits and affective well-being. In an experience sampling study with 396 participants (Mage= 40 years, range 14–88 years, 52% females), we studied how friends/family-contact was associated with Big Five traits and affective well-being across six daily measurements on nine days (average of 55 assessments). Most participants reported more daily contact with family than friends (i.e. held a family orientation), but individual differences were substantial, moderately stable over time, and largely independent from Big Five traits. With advancing age, participants were relatively more often with friends than family. Furthermore, participants were happier when they were with friends compared to family, and this effect was even stronger with higher extraversion. With a unique quantitative test of such differences based on 17,650 social relations of 706 Dutch women (aged 18–41), of whom 40% were considered friends, we examined (a) which kind of personal relations were typically identified as friends (e.g., family, colleague), (b) how this linked to relationship closeness, face-to-face and non-face-to-face contact, and (c) whether these relationship characteristics of friendships differed with age. AboutAbout

Striving for excellence and exploring the impossible and the extraordinary are at the core of who I am. With this mindset, and my background as a pro-athlete I have created in interested in extending the human health and life span. Next to this, I am fascinated by optimization and reaching full potential whether this is related to financial markets, health or energy transition.

------------------------------------------

From the age of 10 to 18, school and sports were my main focus points. I had goals of playing professionally at 16 years old and playing in the US on a scholarship. Next to this, I always wanted to excel at school as well.
When I was 16 years old I made my debut in the Champions League with Standard de Liege and the year after I had won the talent of the year award in Maastricht. Additionally, towards the end of my high school period, I received a scholarship for Providence College to play soccer in the US and I graduated cum laude.

After an extraordinary period in the US, I decided to start focusing more on my education and getting into contact with great minds in academics instead of sports. Although I quit my career as a soccer athlete I still live my life like an athlete on a daily basis. I use my competitiveness, teamwork skills and persistence to solve problems that I face.

To follow my dream of getting challenged in academics I started my double degree program in Applied Mathematics & Computer Science and Engineering at the University of Technology Eindhoven. However, in the few months in between my time in the US and the TU/e I decided to learn a skill I had always wanted: web development. Instead of showing my passion of wanting to create and build on the playing field, I was finally able to explore this passion of mine in a new way.

During my first year at the TU/e, I started my first internship as a software engineer for a fintech company called HiThere. It was a great experience to apply the knowledge I had gained over the past few months in real-life situations. Next to this, I got the opportunity to apply for the Honors program at my university.
